data.content:
These tests are well-structured overall — factory method, clear naming, focused assertions. A few maintainability issues to address:

**1. Flaky time assertion**
```csharp
Assert.IsTrue(token.ExpiresAt > DateTime.UtcNow);
```
This compares against the *real* clock, not your `FakeClock`. If the test runner is slow or the clock ticks between setup and assert, this can flake. Assert against the fake clock's time instead:

```csharp
var clock = new FakeClock(DateTimeOffset.UtcNow);
var service = new TokenService(clock, new InMemoryTokenStore());
var token = service.GenerateToken(email, role);
Assert.IsTrue(token.ExpiresAt > clock.UtcNow);
```

**2. Magic strings repeated across tests**
`"user@example.com"` and `"admin"` appear in 4 tests. If the API changes (e.g., email validation tightens), you update everywhere. Extract constants:

```csharp
private const string DefaultEmail = "user@example.com";
private const string DefaultRole = "admin";
```

**3. `DataRow` couples unrelated scenarios**
The three `DataRow` cases all assert the same thing — they don't actually verify role-specific behavior (full-access vs read-only). If role logic diverges later, you'll need to break this apart anyway. Consider whether these genuinely vary or are just one test with arbitrary inputs.

**Summary:** The big one is **#1** — using the real clock in assertions undermines the purpose of `FakeClock` and will eventually cause intermittent failures. The others are minor but will reduce churn as the codebase grows.
